Favour, in the Original, Grace, that is, the gracefulness of Habit, Gesture, Gate, Discourse, and the Attractives of a hansom Carriage, so as to gain Beholders Love;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 say the Septuagint, the Complaisances of Conversation, which do readily procure peoples Favour and good Opnion. Ag in, Beauty in the Symmetry and Proportion of Parts, in the Feature and
Complexion; That which strikes the Eye and affects the Heart. And yet both these deceitful and vain; for these Reasons.
